Task 1: Understanding and Configuring SELinux
Subtask 1.1: Check Current SELinux Status
First, let's examine the current SELinux configuration on your system.

Step 1: Check the current SELinux enforcement mode

getenforce
Step 2: View detailed SELinux status information

sestatus
Step 3: Check SELinux configuration file

cat /etc/selinux/config
Expected Output Analysis:

Enforcing: SELinux is active and blocking unauthorized actions
Permissive: SELinux is active but only logging violations
Disabled: SELinux is completely turned off
Subtask 1.2: Managing SELinux Enforcement Modes
Step 1: Switch SELinux to permissive mode temporarily

sudo setenforce 0
getenforce
Step 2: Switch back to enforcing mode

sudo setenforce 1
getenforce
Step 3: Make permanent changes to SELinux mode

sudo nano /etc/selinux/config
Modify the SELINUX line to your desired setting:

SELINUX=enforcing
Important Note: Permanent changes require a system reboot to take effect.

Subtask 1.3: Working with SELinux Contexts
Step 1: View SELinux contexts for files

ls -Z /etc/passwd
ls -Z /var/www/html/
Step 2: View SELinux contexts for processes

ps -eZ | grep httpd
ps -eZ | grep sshd
Step 3: View SELinux contexts for users

id -Z
Subtask 1.4: Managing SELinux File Contexts
Step 1: Create a test directory and file

sudo mkdir /test-selinux
sudo touch /test-selinux/testfile.txt
ls -Z /test-selinux/
Step 2: Change SELinux context manually

sudo chcon -t httpd_exec_t /test-selinux/testfile.txt
ls -Z /test-selinux/
Step 3: Restore default SELinux contexts

sudo restorecon -R /test-selinux/
ls -Z /test-selinux/
Subtask 1.5: Working with SELinux Booleans
Step 1: List all SELinux booleans

getsebool -a | head -20
Step 2: Check specific boolean status

getsebool httpd_can_network_connect
Step 3: Modify SELinux boolean temporarily

sudo setsebool httpd_can_network_connect on
getsebool httpd_can_network_connect
Step 4: Make boolean change permanent

sudo setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on
Task 2: Setting Up AppArmor Profiles
Subtask 2.1: Installing and Checking AppArmor Status
Step 1: Install AppArmor utilities (if not already installed)

# For Ubuntu/Debian systems
sudo apt update
sudo apt install apparmor-utils apparmor-profiles

# For CentOS/RHEL systems (if available)
sudo yum install apparmor-utils apparmor-profiles
Step 2: Check AppArmor status

sudo apparmor_status
Step 3: List loaded AppArmor profiles

sudo aa-status
Subtask 2.2: Understanding AppArmor Profile Modes
AppArmor profiles can operate in different modes:

Enforce mode: Actively blocks unauthorized actions
Complain mode: Logs violations but allows actions
Unconfined: No restrictions applied
Step 1: View current profile modes

sudo aa-status | grep profiles
Step 2: Switch a profile to complain mode

sudo aa-complain /usr/bin/ping
sudo aa-status | grep ping
Step 3: Switch a profile back to enforce mode

sudo aa-enforce /usr/bin/ping
sudo aa-status | grep ping
Subtask 2.3: Creating a Custom AppArmor Profile
Step 1: Create a simple test application

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash
echo "Test application starting..."
whoami
date
ls /home/
echo "Test application finished."
Step 2: Make the script executable

sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Step 3: Test the application without AppArmor

/usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Step 4: Generate an AppArmor profile

sudo aa-genprof /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Follow the interactive prompts:

Run the application in another terminal: /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Return to the profile generation terminal
Review and allow necessary permissions
Save the profile
Subtask 2.4: Editing AppArmor Profiles
Step 1: Locate the created profile

sudo ls /etc/apparmor.d/ | grep test-app
Step 2: Edit the profile manually

sudo nano /etc/apparmor.d/usr.local.bin.test-app.sh
Step 3: Add specific permissions to the profile

#include <tunables/global>

/usr/local/bin/test-app.sh {
  #include <abstractions/base>
  #include <abstractions/bash>

  /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh r,
  /bin/bash ix,
  /usr/bin/whoami ix,
  /bin/date ix,
  /bin/ls ix,
  /home/ r,
  /home/*/ r,
}
Step 4: Reload the profile

sudo apparmor_parser -r /etc/apparmor.d/usr.local.bin.test-app.sh
Subtask 2.5: Testing AppArmor Profile Restrictions
Step 1: Test the application with the profile active

/usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Step 2: Modify the script to perform unauthorized actions

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Add this line at the end:

cat /etc/shadow
Step 3: Test the restricted action

/usr/local/bin/test-app.sh
Step 4: Check AppArmor logs for violations

sudo dmesg | grep -i apparmor | tail -10
Or check system logs:

sudo journalctl | grep -i apparmor | tail -10
Task 3: Testing and Troubleshooting SELinux/AppArmor Configurations
Subtask 3.1: SELinux Troubleshooting
Step 1: Install SELinux troubleshooting tools

sudo yum install setroubleshoot-server policycoreutils-python-utils
# or for newer systems
sudo dnf install setroubleshoot-server policycoreutils-python-utils
Step 2: Create a scenario that triggers SELinux denial

sudo mkdir /custom-web
sudo echo "Test content" > /custom-web/index.html
sudo chown -R apache:apache /custom-web/
Step 3: Configure Apache to use the custom directory

sudo nano /etc/httpd/conf.d/custom.conf
Add:

<Directory "/custom-web">
    AllowOverride None
    Require all granted
</Directory>

Alias /custom /custom-web
Step 4: Restart Apache and test

sudo systemctl restart httpd
curl http://localhost/custom/
Step 5: Check SELinux audit logs

sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent
Step 6: Use sealert to analyze denials

sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log
Step 7: Fix the SELinux context issue

sudo semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_exec_t "/custom-web(/.*)?"
sudo restorecon -R /custom-web/
